        "Perform surprise inventory counts and compare results to perpetual inventory records"
      ],
      "correct_answer": 2,
      "explanation": "While all options have investigative value, covert surveillance cameras (option C) would be most effective in directly detecting accomplices helping Miller remove inventory. This approach would reveal who is entering and leaving with Miller during non-business hours and what they are carrying. Option A might show unexplained wealth but wouldn't identify accomplices. Option B focuses on documentation schemes rather than physical theft. Option D would confirm shortages but not identify how inventory is being removed or who else is involved. Surveillance provides real-time evidence of the theft method and participants.",
      "topic": "Asset Misappropriation",
      "subtopic": "Inventory Theft Investigation Techniques",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "num": 12
    },
    {
      "question": "Michael Chen, CFE, is investigating a suspected inventory theft scheme at a manufacturing company. During his investigation, he discovers that the warehouse manager has been creating fictitious sales returns to cover up missing inventory. Which of the following audit procedures would be MOST effective in detecting this type of scheme?",
      "options": [
        "Review sales return documentation for proper authorization and match returned items to inventory receiving records",
        "Perform a ratio analysis comparing cost of goods sold to total revenue over multiple periods",
        "Conduct surprise physical inventory counts and reconcile results to perpetual inventory records",
        "Interview the warehouse manager about inventory control procedures and document the responses"
      ],
      "correct_answer": 2,
      "explanation": "Conducting surprise physical inventory counts and reconciling the results to perpetual inventory records (Option C) is the most effective procedure for detecting fictitious sales returns used to cover inventory theft. This direct verification method would reveal discrepancies between what should be in inventory according to the records (inflated by fake returns) and what is actually physically present. Option A, while useful, may not detect the scheme if the documentation appears proper. Option B might show anomalies but would not directly identify the specific scheme. Option D relies on the potentially dishonest employee's statements and would be the least reliable detection method.",
