      ],
      "correct_answer": 0,
      "explanation": "Comparing current shrinkage rates to historical data and industry benchmarks (Option A) is the most effective initial analytical procedure. Legitimate shrinkage from evaporation should be relatively consistent over time and comparable to industry standards. If the current shortage significantly exceeds these benchmarks, it may indicate theft rather than normal shrinkage. This approach provides objective evidence before pursuing more invasive investigative steps. While interviewing employees (Option B) may be useful later, it's not as effective as analytical comparison. Reviewing personal financial records (Option C) is premature and may violate privacy rights without reasonable suspicion. Immediately reporting to law enforcement (Option D) is inappropriate without completing reasonable due diligence to determine if theft actually occurred.",
